<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
geoe ... @hotmail.com wrote:
&gt; [May] a district court of Maryland issue a
&gt; declaratory judgement . . . . ?
">

For a few kinds of special proceedings, (somewhat) Yes.   E.g., in
case of "[a] petition of injunction filed by . . . [a] person who
brings [some kinds of landlord-tenant proceedings] under § 14-120 of
the Real Property Article" pursuant to Cts. &amp; Jud. Proc. § 4-401(7).

But for almost all other kinds of lawsuits, No.   See § 4-402(c) of
the Cts. &amp; Jud. Proc. Article ("[t]he District Court does not have
jurisdiction to render a declaratory judgment"); Maryland Code, §
3-403(a) of the Cts. &amp; Jud. Proc. Article ("[e]xcept for the District
Court, a court of record within its jurisdiction may declare rights,
status, and other legal relations").

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt; What are the recourses available to get a plaintiff
&gt; to either file suit or just settle in a given timeframe?
">

This question is self-contradictory.   One usually may accurately be
characterized as a "plaintiff" only s/he has commenced a lawsuit
already.   It anyway is too vague to answer because you do not provide
any facts that answer, Why if she has not already done so should that
person file suit or settle in a given timeframe?   Also, if you had
factually reported the relevant specifics of the relationship between
the persons to whom you refer and the nature of the lawsuit and relief
desired by whichever of these persons concerns you, it may be that you
would learn that your first question above also is misleading if you
are presuming by that question that only the grant of an "injunction"
would provide whatever is the relief desired whereas, if one knew what
you were actually asking about in particular re. whatever is the Md.
district court lawsuit in question, there may be other ways that are
indisputably within that court's authority to grant to provide what
may be exactly (or at least tantamount to) whatever that person wants
to accomplish.

