On Jan 31, 7:26 am, geoe ... @hotmail.com wrote:

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt; Can a district court of Maryland issue a declaratory judgement or does
&gt; it have to be in a Circuit court?
">

I assume you mean State district court, not Federal district court.

The MD State District Court is a court of limited jurisdiction, whose
powers are defined by statute.  I'm not aware of any statute that
permits the District Court to hear declaratory judgment actions.   But
check the laws for yourself, including the Declaratory Judgment Act
and the Maryland Rules relating to declaratory judgments, before
deciding.  I am not going to look them up for you.  I am not your
lawyer and this is not to be construed as legal advice.   Do not take
this to the bank or rely upon it if you've got a real matter pending
with something you value at stake.  If so, get yourself a lawyer and
follow his advice.

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt; What are the recourses available to get a plaintiff to either file
&gt; suit or just settle in a given timeframe.
">

Um, it's called the Statute of Limitations.   If a plaintiff doesn't
sue before the applicable statute runs, he's SOL.

For matters that don't have an SOL, the equitable principle of
"laches" may apply.   Colloquially, that is the "You Snooze, You
Looze" rule.   A claim may be barred by the passage of time even if
still technically prosecutable, if the court deems it inequitable to
allow it to proceed, due to fading memory or death of witnesses,
change of circumstances, etc.    Laches generally applies only to
equitable claims, such as for an injunction, an accounting of a trust,
a change in family status, etc. which deal with ongoing matters and
thus are not subject to SOLs.   But if you learn of the existence of
facts that would entitle you to do something about the situation you
complain of in your suit, yet waited an unreasonably long time before
doing anything about it so that the other party would be prejudiced,
the court may uphold this defense.

Other than that, there's not much you the potential defendant can do
to force the plaintiff to sue you.

If you also have an affirmative claim vs. that person, AND if their
potential claim against you is something the law  would consider a
mandatory counterclaim, in some states, you can file your suit against
the other person, and then if the other person wants to have any
chance to raise their own claim, they will be forced to do so as a
counterclaim in the action you brought.   But MD does not generally
recognize the principle of compulsory counterclaims.   The other
person in MD can still bring their claim against you, as  a separate
suit, in the same or a different court, at any time before limitations
run.

